      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Scholars argue that originalism is often a methodological framework where the political preferences of the interpreter become visible, effectively stripping the process of its claimed neutrality. While a scholar might concede that judges cannot escape their own biases, they would counter that originalism forces these biases into the open rather than hiding them behind vague, living-constitution theories. Ultimately, the debate hinges on whether you view the Constitution as a fixed legal text or a blank slate for modern values.",
